-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
--   PARRY ACCURACY SYSTEM  ◈  REAL PRECISION MODEL
--
--   WHAT "ACCURACY" ACTUALLY MEANS:
--   In Blade Ball, the parry window is a brief moment when the ball
--   is close enough to parry (~0.15s before impact). Fire too early
--   = pre-click (misses). Fire too late = gets hit.
--   The PERFECT parry fires exactly when the ball is ~0.2s away.
--
--   HOW AccJitter WORKS:
--   Each frame we compute: shouldFire = (TTI <= IdealWindow + AccJitter)
--   AccJitter is a per-frame random value drawn from [0, maxJitter].
--   maxJitter at acc=100 → 0       (zero noise, always perfect)
--   maxJitter at acc=75  → 0.04s   (fires ±0.04s around ideal)
--   maxJitter at acc=50  → 0.09s   (human-level variance)
--   maxJitter at acc=1   → 0.18s   (very imprecise, often misses)
--
--   AccWindow: the base fire window BEFORE jitter.
--   At acc=100: 0.35s  (fires early enough for all speeds + spam)
--   At acc=50:  0.22s  (normal window)
--   At acc=1:   0.06s  (very narrow, misses fast balls)
--
--   RESULT:
--   acc=100 → catches every ball at the perfect time, every round.
--   acc=50  → catches most balls, occasionally slightly early/late.
--   acc=1   → acts like a human who is not paying attention.
--
--   The key insight: accuracy controls PRECISION not CHEATING.
--   At 100 it fires EXACTLY when it should — not randomly early.
-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

